WEBVTT

00:01.710 --> 00:04.253
(Wil Willis voice-over)
Since the dawn
of human civilization,

00:04.296 --> 00:06.088
mankind has made weapons.

00:06.132 --> 00:08.007
[fire whooshes]
- Whoa!

00:08.050 --> 00:11.218
(Wil)
Bladesmiths have honed
and perfected their craft

00:11.262 --> 00:12.678
over thousands of years.

00:12.722 --> 00:14.555
And now,
for the first time ever,

00:14.598 --> 00:16.181
these men will go head-to-head

00:16.225 --> 00:18.017
and put their skills
to the ultimate test.

00:18.060 --> 00:19.727
Welcome to the forge.

00:19.770 --> 00:22.688
(Wil voice-over)
It starts with a lump
of raw steel

00:22.732 --> 00:24.064
and a ticking clock,

00:24.108 --> 00:25.774
and by the end of three rounds,

00:25.818 --> 00:28.527
the bladesmiths must deliver
handmade weapons

00:28.571 --> 00:29.737
that are works of art

00:29.780 --> 00:32.698
as well as deadly instruments
of war.

00:32.742 --> 00:35.951
These weapons must survive
explosive tests

00:35.995 --> 00:39.371
as well as the scrutiny
of an expert panel judges.

00:39.415 --> 00:43.459
In the end, only one bladesmith
will take home $10,000

00:43.502 --> 00:46.378
and be crowned
a<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

00:46.422 --> 00:49.381
[dramatic music]

00:49.425 --> 00:55.095
♪ ♪

00:55.139 --> 00:57.389
(Murray)
My name's Murray Carter.
I'm a bladesmith.

00:57.433 --> 00:59.725
I've always been fascinated
with knives

00:59.769 --> 01:02.227
and martial weapons growing up.

01:02.271 --> 01:03.771
(Jason)
My name is Jason Morrissey.

01:03.814 --> 01:05.397
My mom had a roommate,

01:05.441 --> 01:07.066
and she was an art teacher,

01:07.109 --> 01:09.026
and she kind of inspired me
to start making things

01:09.070 --> 01:10.277
with my hands.

01:10.321 --> 01:11.987
(Mace)
My name is Mace Vitale.

01:12.031 --> 01:15.240
I run a blacksmithing program
at a local art center.

01:15.284 --> 01:18.786
I'm also a stay-at-home dad
part of the week.

01:18.829 --> 01:20.287
(Ray)
My name is Ray Kirk.

01:20.331 --> 01:23.916
I'm 70 years old,
and I love making metal.

01:23.959 --> 01:25.084
(Wil)
Welcome.

01:25.127 --> 01:26.794
Ahead of you are three rounds,

01:26.837 --> 01:29.755
specifically designed
to test every aspect

01:29.799 --> 01:31.173
of the weapon-making process.

01:31.217 --> 01:32.966
After each round,

01:33.010 --> 01:36.595
you will hand your work over
to our panel of expert judges.

01:36.639 --> 01:38.347
They will decide
who will be crowned

01:38.390 --> 01:39.598
the<i> Forged In Fire</i> champion

01:39.642 --> 01:43.393
and receive a check for $10,000.

01:43.437 --> 01:45.938
Now it's time
to meet our judges.

01:45.981 --> 01:49.566
American Bladesmith Society
master smith, J. Neilson,

01:49.610 --> 01:52.986
historic weapons re-creation
specialist, David Baker,

01:53.030 --> 01:54.404
and internationally known

01:54.448 --> 01:57.116
edged weapons specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:57.159 --> 01:58.951
It's time to get to work.

01:58.994 --> 02:02.746
In front of you on these tables
are a range of materials.

02:02.790 --> 02:05.999
Your challenge is to take
one or more of these items

02:06.043 --> 02:09.962
and reshape and forge that
into a brand-new blade

02:10.005 --> 02:12.297
of your own design.

02:12.341 --> 02:14.174
There's not going
to be anything easy

02:14.218 --> 02:15.634
about forging a blade

02:15.678 --> 02:18.095
with the materials
that are on the table.

02:18.139 --> 02:20.013
Something creative is going

02:20.057 --> 02:22.933
to have to be done in order
to accomplish this task.

02:22.977 --> 02:25.769
(Wil)
This week, the length
of the cutting edge

02:25.813 --> 02:29.815
of your blade
must be at least 9 inches,

02:29.859 --> 02:31.483
and the overall length
of your blade

02:31.527 --> 02:34.486
must be less than 22 inches.

02:34.530 --> 02:38.365
You will have three hours
to forge your blades,

02:38.409 --> 02:40.159
and at the end
of the first round,

02:40.202 --> 02:43.662
one of you will be asked
to surrender his weapon

02:43.706 --> 02:45.289
and dismissed from the forge.

02:45.332 --> 02:46.665
♪ ♪

02:46.709 --> 02:47.708
Good luck, gentlemen.

02:47.751 --> 02:50.335
Your time starts now.

02:50.379 --> 02:51.837
♪ ♪

02:51.881 --> 02:53.547
(Dave)
All right.
The clock is a-ticking.

02:53.591 --> 02:55.674
It looked like Murray
grabbed a ball bearing just now.

02:55.718 --> 02:58.010
- Mace did too.
- And Jason grabbed a blade.

02:58.053 --> 02:59.928
And it looked like he also
grabbed a ball bearing.

02:59.972 --> 03:01.847
(J.)
Ray also grabbed ball bearing.

03:01.891 --> 03:04.516
(Wil)
Every single one of them
snatched up those ball bearings.

03:04.560 --> 03:06.351
(J.)
I think part
of the reasoning being

03:06.395 --> 03:08.896
is 'cause they could take a few
of those and put them together,

03:08.939 --> 03:11.106
forge weld them, and get
enough steel to knock it out.

03:11.150 --> 03:12.691
♪ ♪

03:12.735 --> 03:14.401
One just rolled out
the back side of the oven.

03:14.445 --> 03:16.195
Ball bearings are falling out
of the back of his forge there.

03:16.238 --> 03:17.404
(J.)
Yeah. It's gonna happen.

03:17.448 --> 03:19.323
♪ ♪

03:19.366 --> 03:21.867
(Wil)
Look at that glowing hot
just orb of steel.

03:21.911 --> 03:23.535
- That's beautiful.
- Looks magical.

03:23.579 --> 03:25.370
(J.)
That's great.
I love that.

03:25.414 --> 03:27.206
(Mace)
I took two ball bearings,
and I flattened it out,

03:27.249 --> 03:29.708
and I'm sandwiching them
between some mild steel,

03:29.752 --> 03:31.043
and I'm just gonna
forge out a bar

03:31.086 --> 03:32.878
and make my knife from that.

03:32.922 --> 03:35.797
Everybody seems to have a plan
that they're executing.

03:35.841 --> 03:38.759
(Mace)
My specialty is fighters
and bowies,

03:38.802 --> 03:41.970
and today, I'm gonna
make a big, bad-ass bowie knife.

03:42.014 --> 03:43.388
♪ ♪

03:43.432 --> 03:44.973
I'm gonna make a nice point.

03:45.017 --> 03:47.100
I'm gonna make a
nice, fat, wide, long blade.

03:47.144 --> 03:48.560
♪ ♪

03:48.604 --> 03:50.771
A big knife
in your hand feels really good.

03:50.814 --> 03:52.064
You can chop down a tree
with it.

03:52.107 --> 03:53.607
You could whittle a stick
with it.

03:53.651 --> 03:55.400
You can lop an arm off with it
if you needed to.

03:55.444 --> 03:56.401
How you doing, Ray?

03:56.445 --> 03:58.487
Yeah.
Me too.

03:58.530 --> 04:02.115
(Ray)
As a 70-year-old, this is
a little bit taxing on me...

04:02.159 --> 04:03.200
♪ ♪

04:03.244 --> 04:05.994
but I think my experience

04:06.038 --> 04:09.373
and years will enable
me to kick their ass.

04:09.416 --> 04:14.503
♪ ♪

04:14.546 --> 04:18.090
The blade I'm going to make
is a good camp knife.

04:18.133 --> 04:21.093
It will cut wood, cut steaks.

04:21.136 --> 04:23.929
This is what I love to make.

04:23.973 --> 04:25.806
I really want to win
this competition.

04:25.849 --> 04:28.767
The money will go into a fund
for my children

04:28.811 --> 04:29.935
and my grandchildren.

04:29.979 --> 04:34.439
♪ ♪

04:34.483 --> 04:38.277
Jason's doing some nice work,
drawing out that mower blade.

04:38.320 --> 04:40.028
(Jason)
I'm choosing
the lawnmower blade

04:40.072 --> 04:43.323
because I knew I wanted
to make a nice, thick blade.

04:43.367 --> 04:47.619
I know that I can size it
to a 2-inch thick bar stock.

04:47.663 --> 04:50.330
I plan on making
a full tang chopper

04:50.374 --> 04:52.582
with a little
Persian fighting tip,

04:52.626 --> 04:54.501
and I decided,
just as a backup,

04:54.545 --> 04:57.838
that I would make
two different blades.

04:57.881 --> 04:59.756
I feel good about my decision.

04:59.800 --> 05:02.634
- What do you got going on?
- You'll see.

05:02.678 --> 05:05.137
It look--really looks like
he's making two separate blades,

05:05.180 --> 05:06.388
and he's gonna pick from one.

05:06.432 --> 05:08.140
(Dave)
Seems like a waste of time.

05:08.183 --> 05:10.058
(J.)
Seems like a lot--
a great waste of time.

05:10.102 --> 05:12.811
♪ ♪

05:12.855 --> 05:15.355
Whoo! I'm not used
to working this fast.

05:15.399 --> 05:17.691
Me neither.

05:17.735 --> 05:19.901
(Doug)
Now you can see that Murray's
starting to use a grinder now.

05:19.945 --> 05:21.820
Do you think
he's just cleaning it up

05:21.864 --> 05:24.156
so he could put another one,
to forge weld it?

05:24.199 --> 05:25.824
Yeah.
That's what I'm hoping.

05:25.868 --> 05:27.826
I forged the ball bearing
to a size

05:27.870 --> 05:30.829
that I thought was gonna work
for forge welding.

05:30.873 --> 05:33.081
I measured the mild steel
to that size

05:33.125 --> 05:34.666
and cut the mild steel.

05:34.710 --> 05:36.501
So now I have three
essentially matching wafers.

05:36.545 --> 05:37.919
♪ ♪

05:37.963 --> 05:41.006
The plan is to make
a three-layer laminate,

05:41.050 --> 05:42.716
also known as a San Mai billet.

05:42.760 --> 05:44.092
♪ ♪

05:44.136 --> 05:45.844
(J.)
The outer sides
will be nice and soft.

05:45.888 --> 05:48.180
It'll have that solid,
good steel pour.

05:48.223 --> 05:50.349
That's a smart move.

05:50.392 --> 05:53.769
(Murray)
I'm thinking I will make kind
of a cross between a short sword

05:53.812 --> 05:56.355
and a machete.

05:56.398 --> 05:58.565
(J.)
There's Murray. He's setting
a weld, it looks like.

05:58.609 --> 06:00.359
(Murray)
I'm highly specialized.

06:00.402 --> 06:02.861
Of the 22,000-plus blades
I've made,

06:02.905 --> 06:05.739
about 50%
of those are kitchen knives.

06:05.783 --> 06:07.115
♪ ♪

06:07.159 --> 06:09.242
It's recently come
to my attention

06:09.286 --> 06:12.746
that some of President Obama's
executive chefs

06:12.790 --> 06:15.707
prefer to use my knives
above all others.

06:15.751 --> 06:18.085
This doesn't have to be
the best blade I've ever made.

06:18.128 --> 06:21.880
It just has to be better than
the other competitors' knives.

06:21.924 --> 06:23.048
(Wil)
Bladesmiths,

06:23.092 --> 06:25.217
you have two hours remaining.

06:25.260 --> 06:27.302
You have two hours remaining.

06:27.346 --> 06:32.974
♪ ♪

06:33.018 --> 06:34.726
(J.)
Murray doesn't look
like he's really

06:34.770 --> 06:36.269
got much of a shape on there.

06:36.313 --> 06:37.896
I mean, he's got a basic point,

06:37.940 --> 06:39.773
but he's--
he's left a lot on there.

06:39.817 --> 06:40.982
Kind of got a long,
lean knife.

06:41.026 --> 06:41.983
Yeah.

06:42.027 --> 06:43.610
♪ ♪

06:43.654 --> 06:44.986
(Ray)
I always pay attention
to detail,

06:45.030 --> 06:47.531
because all
of the little details,

06:47.574 --> 06:50.242
if they're not taken care of,
will send you home.

06:50.285 --> 06:54.496
This knife--I want to be
the best that I can make

06:54.540 --> 06:57.040
for whatever
they want to put it through.

06:57.084 --> 06:58.250
♪ ♪

06:58.293 --> 06:59.793
I want to win.

06:59.837 --> 07:01.586
His blade looks small.

07:01.630 --> 07:03.296
That's worrying me.
It's starting to look small.

07:03.340 --> 07:04.631
(Dave)
Yeah. It is looking small.

07:04.675 --> 07:09.761
♪ ♪

07:09.805 --> 07:13.265
(J.)
Mace is using his baseball bat,
and this is an old trick.

07:13.308 --> 07:14.933
If you hit it with the hammer,

07:14.977 --> 07:16.977
it'll mushroom that edge down.

07:17.020 --> 07:19.354
You can get the same effect
with a baseball bat,

07:19.398 --> 07:21.440
so you can straighten
out that back spine

07:21.483 --> 07:26.069
without deforming your edge
very much.

07:26.113 --> 07:28.488
(Dave)
It looks to me like Jason's
still making two blades.

07:28.532 --> 07:30.615
So he's got to decide
which one he wants to keep

07:30.659 --> 07:32.284
and which one
he wants to abandon.

07:32.327 --> 07:34.536
At this point,
I'm super-fatigued.

07:34.580 --> 07:36.621
I had already started
drawing out my guard

07:36.665 --> 07:38.290
on my lawn mower blade,

07:38.333 --> 07:40.792
so I decide just to ditch
my multi-bar construction.

07:40.836 --> 07:42.294
♪ ♪

07:42.337 --> 07:43.837
I hope I made the right choice.

07:43.881 --> 07:45.046
One hour--

07:45.090 --> 07:47.090
you have one hour remaining.

07:47.134 --> 07:49.342
♪ ♪

07:49.386 --> 07:51.636
(J.)
Now the pressure kicks in.

07:51.680 --> 07:54.806
We've still got one smith
who is in his forge.

07:54.850 --> 07:56.975
(Dave)
I can't believe
he wasted as much time

07:57.019 --> 07:57.976
as he did on a second blade.

07:58.020 --> 07:59.186
He'd be on a grinder.

07:59.229 --> 08:00.979
He would be on a grinder
by now

08:01.023 --> 08:02.939
or maybe about 20 minutes ago.

08:02.983 --> 08:05.525
(Jason)
Everybody's getting ready
for heat treat,

08:05.569 --> 08:07.194
and I'm still forging.

08:07.237 --> 08:08.820
I know I need to make a move.

08:08.864 --> 08:14.534
♪ ♪

08:14.578 --> 08:15.911
(J.)
Yeah, I was worried
that Mace's tang

08:15.954 --> 08:18.163
might be
a little on the thin side.

08:18.207 --> 08:21.500
(Wil)
Because we've seen very thin
tangs fail before in the test.

08:21.543 --> 08:23.084
- Correct?
- Oh, absolutely.

08:23.128 --> 08:28.340
♪ ♪

08:28.383 --> 08:30.342
We've got Jason over here,
on the grinder.

08:30.385 --> 08:32.260
He's really throwing
some sparks.

08:32.304 --> 08:34.179
That's good. He needs to.
He's got to make up some time.

08:34.223 --> 08:42.354
♪ ♪

08:42.397 --> 08:43.772
(J.)
Murray's getting ready. Watch.

08:43.815 --> 08:45.607
♪ ♪

08:45.651 --> 08:47.859
I like the fact that he's
moving the blade in and out.

08:47.903 --> 08:49.611
He's got, like,
a nice, even heat.

08:49.655 --> 08:51.446
♪ ♪

08:51.490 --> 08:52.531
Whoo.

08:52.574 --> 08:53.532
[laughter]

08:53.575 --> 08:55.367
What was that?

08:55.410 --> 08:57.536
That's where you transfer
your spirit into the blade.

08:57.579 --> 08:59.704
(Murray)
I don't know what comes out
of my mouth when that happens,

08:59.748 --> 09:02.415
but it's just a verbal
expression of my emotion

09:02.459 --> 09:03.959
at the time.

09:04.002 --> 09:05.418
I'm not even conscious of it
when it happens.

09:05.462 --> 09:07.420
♪ ♪

09:07.464 --> 09:09.464
It's been two years since I've
quenched any blade in oil,

09:09.508 --> 09:12.050
and I pull it out,
and my blade is flaming.

09:12.094 --> 09:14.094
This isn't something
that ever happens to a blade

09:14.137 --> 09:17.472
when you pull it
out of a bucket of water.

09:17.516 --> 09:18.848
(J.)
That is a nice-looking blade.

09:18.892 --> 09:21.560
♪ ♪

09:21.603 --> 09:24.729
I got a big concern right now,
right here, with Jason.

09:24.773 --> 09:27.065
He's got that blade
almost ready to quench.

09:27.109 --> 09:28.900
He does not have a glove on,

09:28.944 --> 09:29.943
and he's got a big blade.

09:29.987 --> 09:31.069
He's gonna burn his hand.

09:31.113 --> 09:32.696
- Oh, [bleep].
- No.

09:32.739 --> 09:35.991
♪ ♪

09:39.955 --> 09:43.832
♪ ♪

09:43.875 --> 09:46.918
I got a big concern right now,
right here, with Jason.

09:46.962 --> 09:49.254
He's got that blade
almost ready to quench.

09:49.298 --> 09:51.172
He does not have a glove on,

09:51.216 --> 09:52.215
and he's got a big blade.

09:52.259 --> 09:53.216
He's gonna burn his hand.

09:53.260 --> 09:54.801
♪ ♪

09:54.845 --> 09:55.969
- Right there, see?
- Yeah.

09:56.013 --> 09:57.387
♪ ♪

09:57.431 --> 09:59.389
He just burned the heck
out of his hands.

09:59.433 --> 10:01.308
♪ ♪

10:01.351 --> 10:03.018
It's not gonna
be a comfortable situation.

10:03.061 --> 10:04.352
Saw that--
saw that coming.

10:04.396 --> 10:05.937
Yeah, you did.

10:05.981 --> 10:07.647
(Jason)
I'm more concerned
about my blade

10:07.691 --> 10:09.608
than I am burning myself.

10:09.651 --> 10:12.277
Working with fire,
you get burned.

10:12.321 --> 10:14.279
Sharp-looking blade,
mister.

10:14.323 --> 10:15.947
- Thanks, bro.
- Looks nice.

10:15.991 --> 10:17.907
- A lot of character.
- Thanks.

10:17.951 --> 10:20.410
(J.)
Even though I'm worried
about Mace's tang,

10:20.454 --> 10:22.412
I love the blade shape.

10:22.456 --> 10:24.456
(Doug)
Well, if he's heat
treating it properly right now,

10:24.499 --> 10:26.124
that thing should hold up.

10:26.168 --> 10:27.792
(Wil)
So Murray is over here.

10:27.836 --> 10:29.127
Any idea what he's doing?

10:29.171 --> 10:30.462
Do you think he's actually done?

10:30.505 --> 10:32.422
- I mean, he could--
- I have no idea.

10:32.466 --> 10:34.466
(Wil)
He could actually be
continuing to work on his blade.

10:34.509 --> 10:36.051
(Murray)
There's always a time

10:36.094 --> 10:37.802
when it's just wise
to set your project down,

10:37.846 --> 10:39.137
and I felt I was at that point.

10:39.181 --> 10:40.805
I've done my best.

10:40.849 --> 10:42.390
I'll let the chips
fall where they may.

10:42.434 --> 10:43.975
(Doug)
Now comes the part where,

10:44.019 --> 10:45.644
"What makes
mine better than yours?"

10:45.687 --> 10:47.771
I'd start working on it.

10:47.814 --> 10:49.022
(J.)
All right.

10:49.066 --> 10:50.398
You've got Ray.
He's quenching.

10:50.442 --> 10:53.234
♪ ♪

10:53.278 --> 10:54.277
(Ray)
Light them up.

10:54.321 --> 10:55.487
(J.)
Got to love it.

10:55.530 --> 10:58.490
I feel very good
about the blade.

10:58.533 --> 11:01.660
I'm going to lay it on the anvil
and go back and sit

11:01.703 --> 11:04.371
and watch the rest of them
for the last 16 minutes.

11:04.414 --> 11:09.292
♪ ♪

11:09.336 --> 11:10.752
- Awesome.
- Oh, look at that.

11:10.796 --> 11:12.462
(J.)
When I'm 70 years old,

11:12.506 --> 11:15.006
I hope I'm still working
as hard as he is at the forge

11:15.050 --> 11:18.176
and producing as good
a quality stuff as he is.

11:18.220 --> 11:20.512
There we go.
In the oil--Mace is in the oil.

11:20.555 --> 11:21.930
I like he put it
all the way in.

11:21.973 --> 11:23.223
He's got a glove on.

11:23.266 --> 11:31.356
♪ ♪

11:31.400 --> 11:33.233
Ten, nine,

11:33.276 --> 11:35.193
eight, seven,

11:35.237 --> 11:37.028
six, five,

11:37.072 --> 11:38.279
four,

11:38.323 --> 11:39.280
three,

11:39.324 --> 11:41.032
two, one.

11:41.076 --> 11:42.534
Gentlemen, stop working.

11:42.577 --> 11:43.535
Stop working.

11:43.578 --> 11:45.120
♪ ♪

11:45.163 --> 11:46.913
(Ray)
I just really feel good
about it.

11:46.957 --> 11:48.707
These other guys ought
to be scared,

11:48.750 --> 11:50.375
'cause the old man
put it on them.

11:50.419 --> 11:52.544
♪ ♪

11:52.587 --> 11:54.212
(Jason)
As I look at my blade,

11:54.256 --> 11:56.256
I'm pretty happy with the shape
of my final product.

11:56.299 --> 11:59.676
I hope the judges will notice
that I put a little extra time

11:59.720 --> 12:01.386
into doing something
a little different,

12:01.430 --> 12:02.762
like a full tang construction.

12:02.806 --> 12:04.389
♪ ♪

12:04.433 --> 12:06.224
Gentlemen,

12:06.268 --> 12:09.269
your challenge is to use one
of the materials provided to you

12:09.312 --> 12:12.564
and reforge and shape
that into a blade

12:12.607 --> 12:15.984
whose cutting edge
was at least 9 inches.

12:16.027 --> 12:18.069
Murray, you're up first.

12:18.113 --> 12:20.905
Please, present your blade
to the judges.

12:20.949 --> 12:25.660
♪ ♪

12:25.704 --> 12:27.746
(J.)
Murray, I like the overall
look of this blade.

12:27.789 --> 12:29.581
That's a nice style.

12:29.624 --> 12:31.583
I was enjoying watching
you do the San Mai setup.

12:31.626 --> 12:33.251
- Thank you.
- Very nice job.

12:33.295 --> 12:35.086
(Doug)
I like the design
of your weapon here.

12:35.130 --> 12:38.173
Very, very clean lines.
It's got a good weight to it.

12:38.216 --> 12:40.675
It feels like a thruster,

12:40.719 --> 12:43.595
but we'll definitely see if
it's gonna do the chopping test

12:43.638 --> 12:44.929
quite well.

12:44.973 --> 12:46.598
Okay, Jason,
you're up next.

12:46.641 --> 12:48.558
Please, present your blade
to the judges.

12:48.602 --> 12:52.479
♪ ♪

12:52.522 --> 12:54.898
(J.)
Well, Jason,
I like the mower blade steel.

12:54.941 --> 12:57.108
You seemed to lose your focus
a bit when

12:57.152 --> 12:59.652
you had to decide which blade
you were gonna go with.

12:59.696 --> 13:01.321
I was super stressed out.

13:01.364 --> 13:02.906
And you burned your hands.
How are you?

13:02.949 --> 13:04.783
- I'm good. I'm good.
- Okay.

13:04.826 --> 13:07.452
I mean, I just--
I was fatigued at that point.

13:07.496 --> 13:09.120
I like this shape.

13:09.164 --> 13:11.039
Overall,
this is gonna be a nice shape,

13:11.082 --> 13:13.666
and your hammer work
was really neat to watch.

13:13.710 --> 13:15.960
You know, I can't help
but wonder again that working

13:16.004 --> 13:17.462
on those two pieces kind

13:17.506 --> 13:19.506
of took away
from where this could've gone.

13:19.549 --> 13:20.590
I agree.

13:20.634 --> 13:21.800
- Thank you.
- Okay.

13:21.843 --> 13:23.176
Mace, you're up next.

13:23.220 --> 13:24.928
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:24.971 --> 13:28.973
♪ ♪

13:29.017 --> 13:30.642
(J.)
Well, Mace, I got to say,
I love the shape of this blade.

13:30.685 --> 13:32.644
Thank you.

13:32.687 --> 13:34.813
There's enough meat back here
to hold up to the chopping.

13:34.856 --> 13:35.980
Thank you.

13:36.024 --> 13:37.690
It's got a good width to it.

13:37.734 --> 13:39.317
It's got a good spine
to support the chop.

13:39.361 --> 13:40.527
You've got a little curve there,

13:40.570 --> 13:42.821
but that can be fixed.

13:42.864 --> 13:44.656
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

13:44.699 --> 13:46.533
(Wil)
Ray, you're up next.

13:46.576 --> 13:49.786
♪ ♪

13:49.830 --> 13:51.663
(J.)
Ray, I got to say,

13:51.706 --> 13:53.331
it was an absolute pleasure
watching you work out there.

13:53.375 --> 13:55.083
All of those years of experience
definitely showed.

13:55.126 --> 13:56.501
You paced yourself
beautifully...

13:56.545 --> 13:58.002
Thank you.

13:58.046 --> 14:00.505
And the shape
of this blade is beautiful.

14:00.549 --> 14:02.382
Very clean lines.

14:02.425 --> 14:04.676
Got a point there for thrusting.

14:04.719 --> 14:06.511
I hope you continue
to share your wisdom, sir.

14:06.555 --> 14:08.054
One of my goals.

14:08.098 --> 14:11.391
This has been one
of our toughest challenges yet.

14:11.434 --> 14:13.434
If you don't mind,
we're going to deliberate.

14:13.478 --> 14:14.686
Thank you.

14:14.729 --> 14:22.360
♪ ♪

14:22.404 --> 14:23.862
(Murray)
What do you think, Jason?

14:23.905 --> 14:24.904
I'm nervous.

14:28.243 --> 14:29.701
[chuckling]

14:29.744 --> 14:32.036
So let's start
with Murray's blade.

14:32.080 --> 14:33.705
(J.)
Well, Murray did a great job.

14:33.748 --> 14:36.374
I was worried
that he used so little steel,

14:36.418 --> 14:38.668
but he's got enough length
on there that I think it's gonna

14:38.712 --> 14:40.086
make a very nice chopper.

14:40.130 --> 14:42.547
Working that ball
bearing material as cold

14:42.591 --> 14:45.800
as he did really gives me
some huge pause

14:45.844 --> 14:49.053
on whether we do have
a hard center in here

14:49.097 --> 14:52.056
or if this is just full
of cracks and being covered.

14:52.100 --> 14:53.683
♪ ♪

14:53.727 --> 14:56.769
Let's go ahead
and move onto Jason's blade.

14:56.813 --> 14:58.980
(Dave)
There's a lot of work
that still needs to be done

14:59.024 --> 15:00.398
with this blade.

15:00.442 --> 15:02.609
I understand, you know,
building a backup plan,

15:02.652 --> 15:05.194
but I think it cost
him work time on this.

15:05.238 --> 15:07.280
Crocodile Dundee would've
been proud of you.

15:07.324 --> 15:09.157
Thanks, man.

15:09.200 --> 15:10.700
(Doug)
As a weapon, it is,
among all the blades--

15:10.744 --> 15:11.910
it's really taken
to consideration

15:11.953 --> 15:13.328
what the challenge would be,

15:13.371 --> 15:15.914
and that is to chop
and do a slice test.

15:15.957 --> 15:18.625
The handle alone lets
you grab onto there

15:18.668 --> 15:20.251
and get a very good,
secure feel.

15:20.295 --> 15:22.253
Let's talk about Mace's blade.

15:22.297 --> 15:24.756
(Doug)
It's light as air.

15:24.799 --> 15:26.591
It's got a good taper to it.

15:26.635 --> 15:27.800
Design-wise--

15:27.844 --> 15:29.886
clean lines, good spine,

15:29.930 --> 15:32.430
good width--
the width for a chopping test.

15:32.474 --> 15:35.099
I like the fact
that he shaped this almost

15:35.143 --> 15:36.434
exclusively with the hammer.

15:36.478 --> 15:38.144
I mean, he did grind the edge,

15:38.188 --> 15:40.563
here, to get it all nice
and cleaned up.

15:40.607 --> 15:44.400
Though there is a little bit
of a warp in his edge

15:44.444 --> 15:46.444
and in his tang.

15:46.488 --> 15:48.446
Let's talk about Ray's blade.

15:48.490 --> 15:50.448
♪ ♪

15:50.492 --> 15:52.367
(Murray)
It looks like they're talking
about yours now, Ray.

15:52.410 --> 15:55.119
That's as big a knife as
I could make out of two balls.

15:55.163 --> 15:56.746
(Murray)
I thought you had
a bigger set than that.

15:56.790 --> 15:58.623
They used to be,
when I was young.

15:58.667 --> 16:00.416
[both chuckle]

16:00.460 --> 16:03.628
Being a smaller blade,
it's still got some heft to it.

16:03.672 --> 16:05.338
(Dave)
But at the same time,

16:05.382 --> 16:07.298
I'm really interested to see,
if he goes forward,

16:07.342 --> 16:09.300
what he's gonna
do with this handle.

16:09.344 --> 16:11.678
It would be nice to see
him put a little bit of a swell

16:11.721 --> 16:13.846
so there's something
to hold onto here.

16:13.890 --> 16:15.014
That's a concern.

16:15.058 --> 16:16.516
♪ ♪

16:16.559 --> 16:18.142
Judges, have you made
your decision?

16:18.186 --> 16:19.852
- Yes.
- Yeah.

16:19.896 --> 16:21.354
- Yeah.
- All right.

16:21.398 --> 16:22.522
Let's go tell our smiths.

16:22.565 --> 16:25.942
♪ ♪

16:25.986 --> 16:27.443
Welcome back.

16:27.487 --> 16:29.237
The judges
have been deliberating,

16:29.280 --> 16:31.948
and they've made a decision.

16:31.992 --> 16:33.908
Now one of you must go home.

16:33.952 --> 16:36.744
♪ ♪

16:36.788 --> 16:39.330
Jason...

16:39.374 --> 16:40.748
You did not make the cut.

16:40.792 --> 16:44.168
♪ ♪

16:44.212 --> 16:47.547
Jason, we all loved where you
were going with that blade,

16:47.590 --> 16:50.508
but with all the time
you spent on another blade

16:50.552 --> 16:51.718
and having a split focus,

16:51.761 --> 16:54.345
I think it cost you in the end.

16:54.389 --> 16:56.597
Jason,
please surrender your weapon.

16:56.641 --> 17:01.644
♪ ♪

17:01.688 --> 17:03.354
(Jason)
I'm super disappointed.

17:03.398 --> 17:06.024
I could've spent a little more
time finishing my blade.

17:06.067 --> 17:09.027
I've really learned that
I need to make solid decisions

17:09.070 --> 17:10.445
and stick to them.

17:10.488 --> 17:11.946
You know,
I can't be wishy-washy.

17:11.990 --> 17:15.199
♪ ♪

17:15.243 --> 17:18.202
Gentlemen, you've made it
through to round two.

17:18.246 --> 17:20.705
Your second challenge
is to finish your work

17:20.749 --> 17:23.791
by turning it
into a fully operational weapon.

17:23.835 --> 17:25.209
♪ ♪

17:25.253 --> 17:27.587
You must craft
and attach a handle

17:27.630 --> 17:30.673
using the range of materials
on the tables in front of you.

17:30.717 --> 17:32.425
♪ ♪

17:32.469 --> 17:35.720
You can also use that time
to address any flaws or issues

17:35.764 --> 17:38.056
in your blade from round one.

17:38.099 --> 17:40.641
You will have three hours
to do this.

17:40.685 --> 17:43.936
After your work is complete,
we will be testing your weapons

17:43.980 --> 17:47.398
for strength and durability
in the coconut chop,

17:47.442 --> 17:49.525
as well as its ability
to hold an edge

17:49.569 --> 17:52.487
in a specially-designed
sharpness test.

17:52.530 --> 17:54.238
At the end of this round,

17:54.282 --> 17:57.909
one of you will be asked
to surrender his weapon

17:57.952 --> 17:59.786
and leave the forge.

17:59.829 --> 18:01.913
Your time starts now.

18:01.956 --> 18:06.667
♪ ♪

18:06.711 --> 18:08.419
(Murray)
We all run up to the table,

18:08.463 --> 18:10.922
and I'm grabbing
for the baseball bat.

18:10.965 --> 18:12.590
How much
of that you gonna use?

18:12.634 --> 18:15.176
Ray gets there before me,
which is fine and dandy.

18:15.220 --> 18:16.469
You know, elders first.

18:16.513 --> 18:18.179
♪ ♪

18:18.223 --> 18:21.015
I let him cut off what he needs,
and then I grab the rest.

18:21.059 --> 18:22.141
Much obliged.

18:22.185 --> 18:24.185
My blade is meant for chopping,

18:24.229 --> 18:27.438
and so it needs to be able to
withstand a little bit of shock,

18:27.482 --> 18:28.815
so I wanted to go
with the hickory.

18:28.858 --> 18:31.109
♪ ♪

18:31.152 --> 18:33.611
Because of the size of my tang,
there is no way

18:33.655 --> 18:37.115
to drill straight down
into a piece of hickory.

18:37.158 --> 18:40.118
My only option
was three slabs of wood,

18:40.161 --> 18:43.621
the middle slab being cut out to
the perfect shape of the tang,

18:43.665 --> 18:47.250
and then all three pieces
of wood sandwiched together.

18:47.293 --> 18:51.462
Basically, he's making
a hidden tang knife with slabs.

18:51.506 --> 18:52.839
(Wil)
That's well thought-out

18:52.882 --> 18:54.465
and well-planned
on Murray's part, I think.

18:54.509 --> 18:56.134
Absolutely.

18:56.177 --> 18:57.510
I think we're seeing a lot of
his craftsmanship

18:57.554 --> 18:58.553
starting to come forward.

18:58.596 --> 19:01.889
♪ ♪

19:01.933 --> 19:03.474
I have a slight bend
in the blade,

19:03.518 --> 19:06.644
so I wanted to straighten
that out right away.

19:06.688 --> 19:09.147
By holding his blade while
heating his tang, he'll know--

19:09.190 --> 19:11.149
He'll know what--
at that temperature's

19:11.192 --> 19:13.151
moving up,
into the blade,

19:13.194 --> 19:14.819
'cause he doesn't want to lose
the temper on that blade.

19:14.863 --> 19:15.862
That'd be terrible.

19:15.905 --> 19:21.325
♪ ♪

19:21.369 --> 19:24.871
(Wil)
It looks like, not only
is Ray gluing his handle on,

19:24.914 --> 19:26.497
he's actually
pinning it in place as well.

19:26.541 --> 19:28.499
Whoa, he set that up quick.

19:28.543 --> 19:30.877
♪ ♪

19:30.920 --> 19:34.255
As soon as I am satisfied
with the glue setting,

19:34.299 --> 19:37.675
I sat down to draw
the profile of the handle

19:37.719 --> 19:39.427
that I'm going to put on it,

19:39.470 --> 19:43.848
and I go to the band saw first
to cut off a large piece of it,

19:43.892 --> 19:45.683
then I used the belt sander

19:45.727 --> 19:49.061
to finish shaping the profile
of my handle.

19:49.105 --> 19:53.441
Ray, it looks like,
is really moving on that handle.

19:53.484 --> 19:57.195
♪ ♪

19:57.238 --> 19:58.863
(Ray)
I have about an hour left,

19:58.907 --> 20:01.199
and I know I'm almost completed,

20:01.242 --> 20:03.576
so I go to the buffer

20:03.620 --> 20:06.746
and use the buffer
to polish the blade

20:06.789 --> 20:09.582
so that it'll be smoother
for the performance test,

20:09.626 --> 20:12.710
and I use it also
to sharpen my blade.

20:12.754 --> 20:15.463
Ray's putting a mirror finish
on his blade at this point.

20:15.506 --> 20:17.006
(J.)
Yeah.
It's--

20:17.050 --> 20:18.507
He's got the handle
dialed in and stained.

20:18.551 --> 20:20.259
♪ ♪

20:20.303 --> 20:22.136
(Wil)
Okay.
So it looks like Ray's finished.

20:22.180 --> 20:24.889
He's laid his handle
on the anvil

20:24.933 --> 20:27.099
with 56 minutes left to go.

20:27.143 --> 20:28.976
Waiting for the glue
to dry or something?

20:29.020 --> 20:31.103
- I'm done.
- Oh, you're all done?

20:31.147 --> 20:33.397
(Murray)
I know he's fast,
but I think he should've just

20:33.441 --> 20:35.399
used every last minute
of the three hours we had.

20:35.443 --> 20:37.902
He's obviously
very confident.

20:37.946 --> 20:41.489
For $10,000,
I hope he's really confident.

20:41.532 --> 20:45.076
♪ ♪

20:49.040 --> 20:55.086
♪ ♪

20:55.129 --> 20:59.131
Ray is really moving
on that handle.

20:59.175 --> 21:01.968
(Dave)
Rays' putting a mirror finish
on his blade at this point.

21:02.011 --> 21:03.552
(J.)
Yeah.
It's--

21:03.596 --> 21:05.137
He's got the handle
dialed in and stained.

21:05.181 --> 21:08.933
♪ ♪

21:08.977 --> 21:10.768
(Wil)
Okay.
So it looks like Ray's finished.

21:10.812 --> 21:13.938
He's laid his handle
on the anvil

21:13.982 --> 21:16.148
with 56 minutes left to go.

21:16.192 --> 21:20.278
I feel good. I feel
that I've done all I can do.

21:20.321 --> 21:22.488
Is anybody gonna make coffee?

21:22.532 --> 21:24.657
Ray put in an order
for coffee.

21:24.701 --> 21:27.410
[both laughing]

21:27.453 --> 21:29.745
♪ ♪

21:29.789 --> 21:32.456
(Ray)
And now
I got a cup of coffee.

21:32.500 --> 21:34.375
I'm relaxing.

21:34.419 --> 21:35.418
I'm enjoying life.

21:35.461 --> 21:37.837
♪ ♪

21:37.880 --> 21:41.173
Making a guard for my knife,
and I'm gonna make a wood handle

21:41.217 --> 21:43.718
out of a piece
of the sledgehammer handle.

21:43.761 --> 21:47.805
I get the guard fit up
pretty close to where I want it,

21:47.849 --> 21:49.849
and now I take my wood

21:49.892 --> 21:53.352
and start to remove material
from the inside of the handle

21:53.396 --> 21:55.896
so I can fit my tang
nice and snug inside.

21:55.940 --> 21:59.734
♪ ♪

21:59.777 --> 22:01.652
Mace just looked at the clock.

22:01.696 --> 22:04.905
He doesn't seem to be happy with
where he is in the progress.

22:04.949 --> 22:06.449
I've got to finish
grinding my blade

22:06.492 --> 22:09.160
and sharpen it and glue
this whole thing together.

22:09.203 --> 22:10.828
♪ ♪

22:10.872 --> 22:13.539
Am I gonna have a knife
by the end of the time is up?

22:13.583 --> 22:15.958
Yup. It's not gonna be pretty.

22:16.002 --> 22:16.959
[laughs]

22:17.003 --> 22:21.630
♪ ♪

22:21.674 --> 22:24.342
Yeah.

22:24.385 --> 22:26.802
(Murray)
With only a few minutes
remaining,

22:26.846 --> 22:29.889
after I sharpened the knife
on the sharpening stone,

22:29.932 --> 22:32.933
I decide to etch the blade
in the chloride.

22:32.977 --> 22:34.226
♪ ♪

22:34.270 --> 22:36.520
And I remove the blade
from the acid,

22:36.564 --> 22:38.230
and I'm just elated.

22:38.274 --> 22:40.358
It looks so beautiful.

22:40.401 --> 22:42.193
(Wil)
Now Murray looks satisfied
with the etch

22:42.236 --> 22:43.235
that he got from the acid.

22:43.279 --> 22:45.363
And my moment of glory

22:45.406 --> 22:47.198
and elation was dashed

22:47.241 --> 22:49.658
when I looked at the handle.

22:49.702 --> 22:53.496
I had all this blue paint
from the cap on the acid jar

22:53.539 --> 22:55.581
all over my hands, and now
it's all over the handle,

22:55.625 --> 22:58.167
and I just know
it's not gonna just brush off.

22:58.211 --> 23:01.504
So I was kind of back to square
one on refinishing the handle.

23:01.547 --> 23:03.089
♪ ♪

23:03.132 --> 23:04.632
(Wil)
Ten, nine,

23:04.675 --> 23:06.801
eight, seven,

23:06.844 --> 23:08.636
six, five,

23:08.679 --> 23:10.930
four, three,

23:10.973 --> 23:12.765
two, one.

23:12.809 --> 23:14.475
Time is up.

23:14.519 --> 23:16.602
♪ ♪

23:16.646 --> 23:19.438
(Mace)
I'm happy
I have a knife completed.

23:19.482 --> 23:21.816
The other guys looked like they
had some pretty good knives.

23:21.859 --> 23:24.193
I think it's gonna be
a tough decision for the judges.

23:24.237 --> 23:25.611
♪ ♪

23:25.655 --> 23:27.279
It's been a wonderful day.

23:27.323 --> 23:29.782
The other knives look very good,

23:29.826 --> 23:31.200
but I believe I can beat them.

23:31.244 --> 23:33.953
♪ ♪

23:33.996 --> 23:35.037
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

23:35.081 --> 23:37.456
this is the weapons test.

23:37.500 --> 23:40.793
First, J. is gonna test
your weapon's strength

23:40.837 --> 23:44.296
and durability
in the coconut chop.

23:44.340 --> 23:45.297
J.

23:45.341 --> 23:47.049
(J.)
All right.

23:47.093 --> 23:49.468
Bladesmiths, I'm gonna
take each of your blades

23:49.512 --> 23:52.054
and attempt to split
three coconuts with them.

23:52.098 --> 23:53.639
♪ ♪

23:53.683 --> 23:56.225
And this is gonna test the
strength of your forged weapon

23:56.269 --> 23:59.311
as well as its ability
to hold onto its edge.

23:59.355 --> 24:00.938
Murray, you're up first.

24:00.982 --> 24:02.273
Don't break it.

24:02.316 --> 24:03.524
That's up to you, not me.

24:03.568 --> 24:04.650
♪ ♪

24:04.694 --> 24:06.193
(Murray)
My heart is racing,

24:06.237 --> 24:09.655
and I'm trying
to will myself to calm down.

24:09.699 --> 24:17.705
♪ ♪

24:27.216 --> 24:29.341
Well, Murray,
it cut really well.

24:29.385 --> 24:33.304
Got through the three coconuts
with no issues at all,

24:33.347 --> 24:35.389
no deformation in the edge,

24:35.433 --> 24:38.058
but we did get a bit
of a bend in the blade.

24:38.102 --> 24:39.810
♪ ♪

24:39.854 --> 24:41.520
But overall,
performed very nicely.

24:41.564 --> 24:44.690
♪ ♪

24:44.734 --> 24:46.192
Mace, what do you think?

24:46.235 --> 24:48.068
- You're ready?
- Hell, yeah.

24:48.112 --> 24:49.904
Let's go for it.

24:49.947 --> 24:51.864
(Mace)
I'm a little nervous
right now.

24:51.908 --> 24:54.074
I'm just hoping it's gonna get
through the coconuts well

24:54.118 --> 24:56.827
and not chip out
or break or anything like that.

24:56.871 --> 25:04.877
♪ ♪

25:13.179 --> 25:15.596
Well, it went
through coconuts, no problem.

25:15.640 --> 25:17.556
Not only went
through the coconuts cleanly,

25:17.600 --> 25:19.433
it bit deeply into the tubes
below it.

25:19.477 --> 25:21.602
♪ ♪

25:21.646 --> 25:24.104
Got a little rushed on
the handle at the end, I think,

25:24.148 --> 25:25.731
but overall, very nice.

25:25.775 --> 25:27.566
Thank you.

25:27.610 --> 25:29.443
Ray, you're up next.
You ready?

25:29.487 --> 25:30.736
You betcha.

25:30.780 --> 25:32.613
(J.)
Let's go.

25:32.657 --> 25:35.908
(Ray)
I am tense about the testing.

25:35.952 --> 25:39.203
The other blades
did exceptionally well,

25:39.247 --> 25:42.498
and I don't know
how my knife will perform.

25:42.542 --> 25:45.000
♪ ♪

25:49.799 --> 25:52.800
♪ ♪

25:52.843 --> 25:54.426
Ray, you're up next.
You ready?

25:54.470 --> 25:55.427
You betcha.

25:55.471 --> 26:03.477
♪ ♪

26:05.856 --> 26:07.982
I am very disappointed
that my blade

26:08.025 --> 26:11.777
did not cut through the second
and third coconut.

26:11.821 --> 26:13.779
Well, Ray, unfortunately,
we had a little trouble

26:13.823 --> 26:15.155
with the coconuts.

26:15.199 --> 26:18.075
We got some deformation
on the edge here,

26:18.119 --> 26:19.493
and I could see some creases

26:19.537 --> 26:21.620
where your two ball bearings
were welded together.

26:21.664 --> 26:23.497
Maybe that left a little bit
of a weak spot

26:23.541 --> 26:25.624
right in that seam, there.

26:25.668 --> 26:27.376
But overall,

26:27.420 --> 26:29.461
it's a beautiful knife,
and it was a pleasure to swing.

26:29.505 --> 26:31.547
I'm gonna pass it off to Doug
now for the sharpness test.

26:31.591 --> 26:33.257
♪ ♪

26:33.301 --> 26:35.676
Okay, Murray, what I'm gonna
do with the sharpness test

26:35.720 --> 26:37.344
is I'm gonna take the blade

26:37.388 --> 26:40.222
and simply do a nice, simple
slice right across a sandbag

26:40.266 --> 26:42.099
to see if it's held its edge.

26:42.143 --> 26:47.771
♪ ♪

26:51.110 --> 26:55.362
♪ ♪

26:55.406 --> 26:57.990
That's a very sharp blade.

26:58.034 --> 27:00.117
Very clean lines right there.

27:00.161 --> 27:01.201
♪ ♪

27:01.245 --> 27:03.787
I'm impressed.

27:03.831 --> 27:05.497
Mace, you ready?

27:05.541 --> 27:06.457
Yes, sir.

27:06.500 --> 27:12.046
♪ ♪

27:15.426 --> 27:18.510
♪ ♪

27:18.554 --> 27:20.054
Like hot metal through butter.

27:20.097 --> 27:21.597
- That is sharp.
- Thank you.

27:21.641 --> 27:24.099
Good job.

27:24.143 --> 27:26.185
Okay, Ray.
Let me just check it out.

27:26.228 --> 27:27.478
I'm ready.

27:27.521 --> 27:32.358
♪ ♪

27:35.613 --> 27:36.820
Nice.

27:36.864 --> 27:38.697
♪ ♪

27:38.741 --> 27:40.949
It's a good slicer.

27:40.993 --> 27:43.369
It's got good feel to it.

27:43.412 --> 27:44.411
Well done.

27:44.455 --> 27:46.372
♪ ♪

27:46.415 --> 27:49.375
(Ray)
It was still sharp enough
to slice through the bag

27:49.418 --> 27:52.127
and the sand,
but when we cut the coconuts,

27:52.171 --> 27:53.879
it failed on two of them.

27:53.923 --> 27:55.255
That could send me home,

27:55.299 --> 27:57.508
and I didn't come up here
to go home.

27:57.551 --> 28:02.262
♪ ♪

28:02.306 --> 28:05.808
The time has come for one
of you to leave the forge.

28:05.851 --> 28:09.561
♪ ♪

28:09.605 --> 28:11.980
Ray, you did not make the cut.

28:12.024 --> 28:13.565
♪ ♪

28:13.609 --> 28:16.777
Ray, you gave us a beautiful
piece of craftsmanship there,

28:16.821 --> 28:18.070
but I think
you ran into a problem

28:18.114 --> 28:19.488
with having two ball bearings,

28:19.532 --> 28:21.073
and you had the seam
of that weld

28:21.117 --> 28:23.033
running down the center
of the blade,

28:23.077 --> 28:24.618
and that caused a weakness
in your edge,

28:24.662 --> 28:26.120
and you weren't able to cut
through two

28:26.163 --> 28:27.454
of our three coconuts.

28:27.498 --> 28:28.747
♪ ♪

28:28.791 --> 28:30.916
Ray,
please surrender your weapon.

28:30.960 --> 28:32.626
♪ ♪

28:32.670 --> 28:35.754
I feel the judges
made the correct decision.

28:35.798 --> 28:37.172
Thank you, Ray.

28:37.216 --> 28:38.924
It just happened
that this particular blade

28:38.968 --> 28:40.926
that I made
did not stand up this time.

28:40.970 --> 28:46.557
♪ ♪

28:46.600 --> 28:48.100
Congratulations.

28:48.144 --> 28:50.269
You have both made it
through the second round

28:50.312 --> 28:52.521
and are now
one round closer to the title

28:52.565 --> 28:53.814
of<i> Forged In Fire</i> champion

28:53.858 --> 28:55.607
and a check for $10,000.

28:55.651 --> 28:59.027
Now we're asking you
to forge a weapon

28:59.071 --> 29:01.655
whose origins go back thousands
of years...

29:01.699 --> 29:03.907
♪ ♪

29:03.951 --> 29:05.159
The Moro kris.

29:05.202 --> 29:07.369
♪ ♪

29:07.413 --> 29:12.458
(Wil)
The kris came into existence
around 1361 A.D. in the kingdom

29:12.501 --> 29:15.252
of Majapahit, East Java.

29:15.296 --> 29:17.045
Believed
to be the primary weapons

29:17.089 --> 29:18.797
wielded by Asian warriors,

29:18.841 --> 29:20.466
its distinctive wavy blade

29:20.509 --> 29:22.801
creates a wider wound
during combat,

29:22.845 --> 29:25.429
causing the victim
to quickly bleed to death.

29:25.473 --> 29:27.848
The hilt is viewed
as a work of art

29:27.892 --> 29:30.142
and is often carved
in meticulous detail

29:30.186 --> 29:33.145
from precious wood,
gold, or ivory.

29:33.189 --> 29:34.855
In popular culture,

29:34.899 --> 29:38.233
the kris can be seen
in the video game<i> Mortal Kombat.</i>

29:38.277 --> 29:39.943
♪ ♪

29:39.987 --> 29:42.154
Your challenge is to forge

29:42.198 --> 29:44.990
an effective,
fully-functional version

29:45.034 --> 29:47.326
of that ancient
and beautiful weapon.

29:47.369 --> 29:48.827
(Mace)
The waves in the blade

29:48.871 --> 29:50.996
and the shape
of it is gonna be a challenge.

29:51.040 --> 29:53.207
(Murray)
I've never made
a Moro kris before,

29:53.250 --> 29:56.210
but I feel very confident
that I can turn out a truly

29:56.253 --> 29:57.878
high-performance weapon.

29:57.922 --> 29:59.505
You will have five days

29:59.548 --> 30:02.007
at your home forge
to complete this challenge.

30:02.051 --> 30:04.343
After those five days,
you will come back

30:04.386 --> 30:07.012
and present your kris
to our panel of judges.

30:07.056 --> 30:09.014
They will subject them
to a series

30:09.058 --> 30:11.308
of rigorous and dynamic tests.

30:11.352 --> 30:12.851
When the tests are complete,

30:12.895 --> 30:14.520
our judges will decide
who will be crowned

30:14.563 --> 30:16.355
the<i> Forged In Fire</i> champion

30:16.398 --> 30:20.359
and receive a check
for $10,000.

30:20.402 --> 30:21.777
Good luck, bladesmiths.

30:21.821 --> 30:23.362
We will see you in five days.

30:23.405 --> 30:31.870
♪ ♪

30:31.914 --> 30:34.039
(Murray)
I've never made a Moro kris
before,

30:34.083 --> 30:36.375
but size-wise, I'm comfortable
with the project,

30:36.418 --> 30:39.378
but there's a lot of details
that I need to learn about.

30:39.421 --> 30:41.380
So I'm sanding
the cardboard version

30:41.423 --> 30:43.215
so that I can develop
muscle memory.

30:43.259 --> 30:44.883
So by the time
I get to the real blade,

30:44.927 --> 30:46.844
I'll be a little bit
familiar with the grinding.

30:49.431 --> 30:51.557
♪ ♪

30:51.600 --> 30:52.558
To fuller or not to fuller?

30:52.601 --> 30:54.226
That definitely is the question,

30:54.270 --> 30:57.896
and I've never done a fullering
in blades before.

30:57.940 --> 31:00.065
Even if I lose the competition,
I've learned a new skill.

31:00.109 --> 31:01.483
♪ ♪

31:01.527 --> 31:02.901
If this fullering
doesn't go right,

31:02.945 --> 31:05.237
or if I get it too thin
or inconsistent,

31:05.281 --> 31:06.572
I'm gonna
have to forge a new blade,

31:06.615 --> 31:07.656
and that's gonna
be a major setback.

31:07.700 --> 31:15.497
♪ ♪

31:15.541 --> 31:17.291
(Mace)
When I first started
bladesmithing,

31:17.334 --> 31:19.126
I took an intro
to bladesmithing class,

31:19.169 --> 31:22.254
and in that class, I actually
made a couple of kris blades.

31:22.298 --> 31:24.590
♪ ♪

31:24.633 --> 31:27.467
I plan on constructing
a 23-layer.

31:27.511 --> 31:29.761
Little of the Damascus
to make the sword from.

31:29.805 --> 31:33.098
Seven layers
for each of my competitors

31:33.142 --> 31:36.518
and a layer for my daughter,
a layer for my wife.

31:36.562 --> 31:38.312
I'm gonna put a little magic
into that blade.

31:38.355 --> 31:43.650
♪ ♪

31:43.694 --> 31:47.696
So my fear today is that I
won't get a perfect heat treat.

31:47.740 --> 31:50.157
It could get too hot
in some places

31:50.200 --> 31:52.367
or not hot enough
in other places.

31:52.411 --> 31:53.785
It's kind of difficult
in my little

31:53.829 --> 31:55.787
forge to heat up
such a large blade.

31:55.831 --> 31:58.498
It's all done
with the human senses,

31:58.542 --> 32:00.208
so anything can happen.

32:00.252 --> 32:02.169
♪ ♪

32:02.212 --> 32:04.004
[grunts]

32:04.048 --> 32:12.054
♪ ♪

32:15.017 --> 32:17.059
No. It's got to be--it's got
to be heated higher.

32:17.102 --> 32:18.644
Damn it.

32:18.687 --> 32:20.437
Now I've got to go back
and quench it again.

32:20.481 --> 32:21.980
♪ ♪

32:22.024 --> 32:23.982
Today should be
a little bit easier.

32:24.026 --> 32:25.692
I don't have to do
all the hot work.

32:25.736 --> 32:28.695
My plan is to go
to my other shop

32:28.739 --> 32:29.863
and get it heat treated.

32:29.907 --> 32:34.576
♪ ♪

32:34.620 --> 32:35.827
Shazam!

32:35.871 --> 32:39.581
♪ ♪

32:39.625 --> 32:40.999
Quenching seemed to go good.

32:41.043 --> 32:43.377
I didn't hear any tings,
so hopefully,

32:43.420 --> 32:44.670
we've got a good, viable blade.

32:44.713 --> 32:50.342
♪ ♪

32:50.386 --> 32:52.219
(Murray)
The second quench went okay,

32:52.262 --> 32:54.888
and now I'm gonna
assemble the handle,

32:54.932 --> 32:56.682
and I'm gonna get
it all finished up.

32:56.725 --> 33:00.018
I decided to go
with a multipiece construction

33:00.062 --> 33:02.980
for the handle that doesn't
require any drilling

33:03.023 --> 33:05.273
through the tang, which would
potentially weaken it.

33:05.317 --> 33:08.652
♪ ♪

33:08.696 --> 33:12.364
I know I've done my absolute
best with this project.

33:12.408 --> 33:14.074
I'm all ready
for this competition.

33:14.118 --> 33:16.576
♪ ♪

33:16.620 --> 33:17.577
Cut through this one too.

33:17.621 --> 33:19.705
♪ ♪

33:19.748 --> 33:21.581
(Mace)
Throughout my work,
I've been trying to harness

33:21.625 --> 33:23.458
the spirit of the tiger
and put that in my sword.

33:23.502 --> 33:25.210
♪ ♪

33:25.254 --> 33:26.294
[whistles]

33:28.007 --> 33:29.381
The blade's gonna
have some stripes.

33:29.425 --> 33:31.216
The handle's gonna
have some stripes,

33:31.260 --> 33:33.760
tiger claws,
a little tiger tooth.

33:33.804 --> 33:34.761
♪ ♪

33:34.805 --> 33:36.638
I'm gonna win.

33:36.682 --> 33:38.890
Tigers are winners,
and I am the tiger.

33:38.934 --> 33:44.771
♪ ♪

33:47.818 --> 33:55.240
♪ ♪

33:55.284 --> 33:59.202
Murray, Mace,
welcome back to the forge.

33:59.246 --> 34:02.831
You had five days at your home
forge to work on your krises.

34:02.875 --> 34:05.584
Mace, tell us a little bit
about your weapon.

34:05.627 --> 34:07.085
♪ ♪

34:07.129 --> 34:10.589
(Mace)
I did a 23-layer blade.

34:10.632 --> 34:11.840
I made the steel
with my power hammer,

34:11.884 --> 34:13.633
but forged the entire blade
by hand.

34:13.677 --> 34:16.428
I forged in all the waves,
and I forged in all the bevels.

34:16.472 --> 34:17.763
I forged the point.

34:17.806 --> 34:19.765
I tried to put magic
into that blade.

34:19.808 --> 34:22.184
Murray, can you tell us
a little bit about your blade?

34:22.227 --> 34:24.019
♪ ♪

34:24.063 --> 34:26.063
(Murray)
I've never made a blade
like this before,

34:26.106 --> 34:28.982
but from having made
over 22,000 blades,

34:29.026 --> 34:30.442
it seemed to me obvious

34:30.486 --> 34:32.778
that this was definitely
a thrusting weapon,

34:32.821 --> 34:34.821
also for some slicing
and chopping.

34:34.865 --> 34:38.366
That being the case, I
chose a laminate of spring steel

34:38.410 --> 34:41.953
on the outside and a Hitachi
blue super steel core.

34:41.997 --> 34:43.830
It was a journey making this,

34:43.874 --> 34:46.875
and I hope that my spirit
is in the blade.

34:46.919 --> 34:48.043
♪ ♪

34:48.087 --> 34:50.962
Gentlemen,
they certainly look great,

34:51.006 --> 34:54.633
but beauty is secondary
to performance.

34:54.676 --> 34:58.929
All that matters now is how they
perform in our weapons test.

34:58.972 --> 35:01.973
Each of your blades will be put
through three trials.

35:02.017 --> 35:04.392
This is the slice test.

35:04.436 --> 35:05.393
Doug.

35:05.437 --> 35:09.147
♪ ♪

35:09.191 --> 35:12.651
The unique design of a Moro
kris is even made more distinct

35:12.694 --> 35:15.320
by its fluid, wavelike edges.

35:15.364 --> 35:16.822
It can thrust,

35:16.865 --> 35:19.908
but its primary purpose
is slashing and chopping.

35:19.952 --> 35:21.368
To test your kris' ability

35:21.411 --> 35:23.703
to perform according
to its ancient design,

35:23.747 --> 35:27.582
I will use it to chop and slice
against these moving targets.

35:27.626 --> 35:29.209
Mace, you're up first.
Are you ready?

35:29.253 --> 35:30.293
Sure.

35:30.337 --> 35:38.343
♪ ♪

35:41.849 --> 35:43.056
Nice.

35:43.100 --> 35:44.057
♪ ♪

35:44.101 --> 35:45.350
Nice balance.

35:45.394 --> 35:46.685
Nice recovery.

35:46.728 --> 35:48.270
Allows you to just move
with the blade.

35:48.313 --> 35:49.688
Good job.

35:49.731 --> 35:50.730
Thank you.

35:50.774 --> 35:51.898
Murray, you're next.
You ready?

35:51.942 --> 35:53.108
I certainly am.

35:53.152 --> 36:01.158
♪ ♪

36:07.166 --> 36:08.957
Well, Murray,

36:09.001 --> 36:12.627
the balance of this blade
allows me to chase an attack,

36:12.671 --> 36:14.045
and it will come with me.

36:14.089 --> 36:16.214
On the recovery
to go to another attack,

36:16.258 --> 36:17.340
it will stay with me.

36:17.384 --> 36:19.885
It doesn't go away from me.

36:19.928 --> 36:21.553
It will slice.
Good job.

36:21.597 --> 36:23.221
Thank you.

36:23.265 --> 36:25.557
The quality of the cut
is obvious to the human eye.

36:25.601 --> 36:29.144
My blade was the sharper
and more cleanly cutting blade.

36:29.188 --> 36:30.562
♪ ♪

36:30.606 --> 36:32.564
To test the lethality
of your kris,

36:32.608 --> 36:34.149
I will take your weapon,

36:34.193 --> 36:36.234
and I'm gonna strike
into this animal carcass.

36:36.278 --> 36:37.736
Mace, you're up first.
Are you ready?

36:37.779 --> 36:38.737
Yes, sir.

36:38.780 --> 36:46.786
♪ ♪

36:49.625 --> 36:52.417
Well, it cut cleanly
through the spine,

36:52.461 --> 36:57.214
all the way through the meat
in one big, sweeping slash.

36:57.257 --> 36:59.090
It will kill.
Good job.

36:59.134 --> 37:00.425
Thank you very much.

37:00.469 --> 37:01.843
Murray, you're up next.
You ready?

37:01.887 --> 37:03.261
Yeah.

37:03.305 --> 37:11.311
♪ ♪

37:15.150 --> 37:16.399
When cutting through,

37:16.443 --> 37:19.444
there was a slight drag
in the cut,

37:19.488 --> 37:21.279
but it did cut very cleanly,
through.

37:21.323 --> 37:24.449
It's a very, very sharp blade.

37:24.493 --> 37:26.451
It will kill.

37:26.495 --> 37:29.788
Doug's not giving me positive
feedback about the way it cut,

37:29.831 --> 37:31.498
but I know that often,

37:31.541 --> 37:35.126
it can just be the angle of
the blade edge in relationship

37:35.170 --> 37:36.586
to the motion of the arm.

37:36.630 --> 37:40.048
♪ ♪

37:40.092 --> 37:42.801
Bamboo is
a very durable material.

37:42.844 --> 37:47.264
Ounce for ounce, it is stronger
than concrete, brick, or wood.

37:47.307 --> 37:48.723
To test the strength
of your kris,

37:48.767 --> 37:50.809
I will delivery four strikes
into the bamboo

37:50.852 --> 37:53.228
to see how well
your weapon stands up.

37:53.272 --> 37:55.146
Mace, you're up.

37:55.190 --> 37:57.357
(Mace)
I'm confident
in my construction methods,

37:57.401 --> 38:01.319
but there's always that fear
that your blade will come apart.

38:01.363 --> 38:02.570
I'm a bit nervous.

38:02.614 --> 38:10.620
♪ ♪

38:17.087 --> 38:22.757
♪ ♪

38:22.801 --> 38:26.177
Well, no damage
to the blade, sir.

38:26.221 --> 38:27.679
It chopped nicely,

38:27.723 --> 38:29.681
but of the couple
of times over there,

38:29.725 --> 38:31.641
it did want to fall
out of my hand,

38:31.685 --> 38:34.519
just because it's so heavy
on the blade.

38:34.563 --> 38:37.522
But none the less, it looks
like your edge did hold up.

38:37.566 --> 38:39.691
- Excellent.
- Murray, you're up next.

38:39.735 --> 38:41.860
- You ready?
- Yes, I am.

38:41.903 --> 38:43.903
I tested my kris
on some tree branches,

38:43.947 --> 38:45.780
and it cut very well,

38:45.824 --> 38:48.616
but there's a big difference
between cutting live wood

38:48.660 --> 38:49.784
and dead bamboo.

38:49.828 --> 38:57.751
♪ ♪

39:00.797 --> 39:04.382
♪ ♪

39:04.426 --> 39:05.550
(Doug)
Murray, you're up.

39:05.594 --> 39:08.011
- You ready?
- Yes, I am.

39:08.055 --> 39:16.061
♪ ♪

39:23.612 --> 39:31.242
♪ ♪

39:31.286 --> 39:32.911
Okay, Murray,
it looks like your blade edge

39:32.954 --> 39:34.913
held up with the chops.

39:34.956 --> 39:38.124
It almost clearly
sliced all the way through.

39:38.168 --> 39:39.584
But there is now an issue

39:39.628 --> 39:41.503
that we're looking
at with your blade.

39:41.546 --> 39:43.922
I think there might be
a little bend here,

39:43.965 --> 39:46.716
caused from chopping
into the bamboo,

39:46.760 --> 39:50.720
but other than that,
it still has a very sharp edge.

39:50.764 --> 39:52.097
The strength of the blade
held up.

39:52.140 --> 39:53.098
Good job.

39:53.141 --> 39:54.099
Thank you.

39:54.142 --> 39:55.975
♪ ♪

39:56.019 --> 39:58.103
(Mace)
I'm pleased with
the performance of my blade,

39:58.146 --> 40:00.772
but I think Murray's blade
did well, too,

40:00.816 --> 40:03.525
and I think it's gonna be
a tough decision for the judges.

40:03.568 --> 40:08.279
♪ ♪

40:08.323 --> 40:11.616
Gentlemen, both of you have
been outstanding competitors

40:11.660 --> 40:13.284
through three rounds
of competition.

40:13.328 --> 40:14.994
In five days,

40:15.038 --> 40:17.414
you have fabricated
fully functioning Moro krises

40:17.457 --> 40:19.457
that you
should both be proud of,

40:19.501 --> 40:21.251
but there can only
be one champion.

40:21.294 --> 40:23.962
♪ ♪

40:24.005 --> 40:25.338
(J.)
Well, Mace,

40:25.382 --> 40:28.299
I love the overall construction
of your blade.

40:28.343 --> 40:30.093
The steel came out
beautifully.

40:30.137 --> 40:31.136
You've got a nice pattern.

40:31.179 --> 40:32.804
♪ ♪

40:32.848 --> 40:35.306
You did deliver the blade
with a bit of a slight twist

40:35.350 --> 40:37.016
in there,

40:37.060 --> 40:39.477
and that worried me about the
overall integrity of the blade.

40:39.521 --> 40:41.020
♪ ♪

40:41.064 --> 40:42.981
I really like the shape
of your handle.

40:43.024 --> 40:44.983
I think it's very comfortable
in the hand.

40:45.026 --> 40:48.486
I'm not really fond of the way
it transitions into the guard,

40:48.530 --> 40:52.198
and I do find the blade
a little bit heavy at the tip.

40:52.242 --> 40:54.117
But in the kill test,

40:54.161 --> 40:56.786
it passed through that meat
as if it wasn't there.

40:56.830 --> 40:57.829
♪ ♪

40:57.873 --> 40:58.788
Thank you.

40:58.832 --> 40:59.998
♪ ♪

41:00.041 --> 41:01.082
(Wil)
Murray, you're next.

41:01.126 --> 41:02.709
♪ ♪

41:02.752 --> 41:06.713
Murray, the balance
in your blade is phenomenal,

41:06.756 --> 41:09.257
but the problem I had
was doing the cuts on the bamboo

41:09.301 --> 41:11.009
during the strength test.

41:11.052 --> 41:13.553
Because you designed it as a
thruster rather than a chopper,

41:13.597 --> 41:16.639
the alignment of your handle
made it move around.

41:16.683 --> 41:18.224
♪ ♪

41:18.268 --> 41:20.602
Murray, your sword--
it's a work of art.

41:20.645 --> 41:23.021
The transition from the pommel
to the handle

41:23.064 --> 41:24.606
to the guard to the blade--

41:24.649 --> 41:26.941
it's all smooth, flawless,

41:26.985 --> 41:28.860
but that bend in the blade

41:28.904 --> 41:31.404
is telling me that somewhere
in that blade is a soft spot.

41:31.448 --> 41:36.242
♪ ♪

41:36.286 --> 41:39.954
Gentlemen, you
have both done immaculate work.

41:39.998 --> 41:42.248
However, in this forge,

41:42.292 --> 41:45.293
there can only be one winner
of $10,000.

41:45.337 --> 41:49.380
♪ ♪

41:49.424 --> 41:51.132
Mace...

41:51.176 --> 41:53.384
You are
the<i> Forged In Fire</i> champion.

41:53.428 --> 41:55.553
- Yes!
- Congratulations.

41:55.597 --> 41:57.013
- Thank you, Murray.
- Nice job, man.

41:57.057 --> 41:58.598
- Thanks very much.
- I'm happy for you.

41:58.642 --> 42:02.352
Murray, unfortunately,
your kris did not make the cut.

42:02.395 --> 42:04.395
Murray, I find that weapon

42:04.439 --> 42:06.231
absolutely beautiful
and comfortable,

42:06.274 --> 42:10.235
but the fact that there's
a soft core in there somewhere

42:10.278 --> 42:12.237
and that it picked up a bend

42:12.280 --> 42:14.948
where your opponent's blade
did not--

42:14.991 --> 42:16.491
that was the deciding factor,

42:16.535 --> 42:18.243
and that's
why we had to let you go.

42:18.286 --> 42:19.577
♪ ♪

42:19.621 --> 42:21.579
Murray, please,
surrender your weapon.

42:21.623 --> 42:22.997
♪ ♪

42:23.041 --> 42:24.916
While there's always
a disappointment

42:24.960 --> 42:27.293
when one puts their best effort
forward and doesn't win...

42:27.337 --> 42:28.586
Thank you, gentlemen.

42:28.630 --> 42:30.129
- Thank you, Murray.
- Thank you.

42:30.173 --> 42:32.966
I do feel an overwhelming
sense of gratitude

42:33.009 --> 42:35.343
for having been
able to participate.

42:35.387 --> 42:38.471
Mace made the better blade,
and I'm proud of him.

42:38.515 --> 42:39.764
♪ ♪

42:39.808 --> 42:41.266
Mace, congratulations.

42:41.309 --> 42:42.809
Whoo!

42:42.852 --> 42:44.936
Mace, fantastic.

42:44.980 --> 42:46.521
I mean, the steel's beautiful.

42:46.565 --> 42:49.315
I like how you did the file work
on the blade.

42:49.359 --> 42:51.150
The blade held up beautifully.

42:51.194 --> 42:53.111
The edge is razor sharp.

42:53.154 --> 42:55.113
You should be exceptionally
proud of that piece.

42:55.156 --> 42:56.614
You did a great job.

42:56.658 --> 42:58.157
(Mace)
I'm the<i> Forged In Fire</i> champion.

42:58.201 --> 42:59.951
I feel good,

42:59.995 --> 43:01.369
and I'm glad I came out on top.

43:01.413 --> 43:02.495
I'm the tiger.

43:02.539 --> 43:07.542
♪ ♪
